<br>
How I would test it is to keep everything constant in regards to defensive abilities, even AGI, preferably of course at 255 since thats easy to get to, and then I would attempt to vary my AC at around 50 point intervals from 1000, to as high as it could go.<br>
<br>
I would take 10+ minute logs against a variety of fixed level creatures, at all AC points.  You attacking or riposting attacks or the mob riposting you, don't really matter.  I'd consider the sole thing of importance to be the Average damage per hit from each mob at each ac point.<br>
<br>
So you'd go from say Bloodmaw in gd at the low end, up to Yelinak at the high end, testing each, for say 15 minutes at each AC point (Lets say 8-10 different ac points).  There are a lot of fixed level mobs but you'd want to say, get them about 10 level gaps.  So a level 30 mob, a level 40 one, 50.. etc..<br>
<br>
This would give you a lot of information about usefulness of AC values against mobs of different levels.  I don't really think you can draw entire conclusions based entirely on one set of logs from yelinak about an AC cap.  And also testing multiple mobs would let you know if the 'cap' is really just related to the level/attack of the mob you're fighting. <br>
<br>
It could be the case, that say the mist panther, because of his level and attack, that anything beyond say 1100 AC does not lower damage, but then on something say thats level 62, if you see that, anything beyond 1150 has no effect on damage taken you could infer that the cap is based on level/attack of the mob and not some fixed number. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ubrutultarewmarr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brutul Tarew Marr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 153<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 6:12:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.blackcompany.cc/member_pics/45.jpg height=185 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> Average damage per hit measures damage mitigation, but not avoidance.  I think you need to measure damage taken per second to get an accurate test.  Just looking at the average damage per hit won't tell you if you are being missed more because of your ac, which is a very important piece of information. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6629>Brutul Vilesilencer</a><br>

