<br>
To test avoidance AC is a seperate thing, relating solely to the hit/miss % chance that a mob has when you vary your avoidance AC (agility is about the only thing I can think of for a player to adjust with this).<br>
<br>
Average damage per hit, does not factor in avoidance at all, it only is the average of the hits, which is mitigation, and which is probably what matters most to people.  If you're asking if say a 10 ac upgrade is better than a 50hp one, you're asking about mitigation AC upgrade, vs a hp upgrade, avoidance isnt part of that at all.<br>
<br>
so basically, assuming your agi is constant at say 255, and you change only your AC via armor chances/removals, you are modifying ONLY mitigation AC, and the hit/miss ratio from the mob to you, should remain the same. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ubrutultarewmarr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brutul Tarew Marr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 7:27:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.blackcompany.cc/member_pics/45.jpg height=185 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> Is  your assertion that the only thing that affects how often a mob misses  you is Agility?  If so then we should all be maxing our agility above most other stats.  <br>
